No I highly disagree with the above. The linalg in 189 is pretty much about calculation and proof by calculation. However those topics are just extending 54 further. 110 teaches you the abstraction of the world which is another dimension of linalg. The entire modern math is about building structures, abstraction and relationship about the world.
If you have taken cs 189, then taking math 110 is redundant. However, math 110 is a good technical elective

children.subject: I just wanted to note that not all offerings of 110 are necessarily "redundant". My experience with 110 was probably different to most as I took it with Prof Holtz, who most would agree teaches the class very differently to others to the point where past midterms and finals were of no use for studying. I have not taken any class with Frenkel so I can't speak to this offering of 110 in particular. The class (with Holtz) is not computational at all but rather abstract to the point where we didn't even talk about topics like traces or determinants. Having taken 189 and 127, I found there to be barely any overlap other than some talk about real symmetric matrices (which was hardly talked about in 189) - 110 did not help with 127/189 or the other way around. As such I think the class (with this professor in particular) has a lot of content that you likely would not have studied. That said, I don't know how useful it would be for you - it depends on your background and whether you're interested in more theoretical/abstract topics. If you want a more rigorous/less computational study of linear algebra and an introduction to more abstract notions in linear algebra (but you don't want to take H110 or are not sure about taking 113) then taking Holtz's version of the course could be a good idea (from a learning perspective). The textbook used was Linear Algebra Done Right, so I'd imagine that other versions of 110 using this textbook might be similarly taught.
